body:
In all our `Smart` classes, a new `SmartJson` object is created every time we try to read `JSON` data from it. Take for example the following code from `Comment.Smart`:

```
/**
 * Get its URL.
 * @return URL of comment
 * @throws IOException If there is any I/O problem
 */
public URL url() throws IOException {
    return new URL(new SmartJson(this).text("url"));
}
/**
 * When this comment was created.
 * @return Date of creation
 * @throws IOException If there is any I/O problem
 */
public Date createdAt() throws IOException {
    try {
        return new Github.Time(
            new SmartJson(this).text("created_at")
        ).date();
    } catch (ParseException ex) {
        throw new IOException(ex);
    }
}
```

Repeated creation of `SmartJson` is not necessary, since `SmartJson` is immutable and so are the `Smart` classes that use it. It will be just as safe and will be faster and more memory efficient if we store it as a final field and reuse it every time we need to fetch a `JSON` attribute.

Like so:

```
/**
 * SmartJson object for convenient JSON parsing.
 */
private final transient SmartJson jsn;

/**
 * Public ctor.
 * @param cmt Comment
 */
public Smart(Comment cmt) {
    //...existing constructor code
   this.jsn = new SmartJson(cmt);
}
//...*snip*...
/**
 * Get its URL.
 * @return URL of comment
 * @throws IOException If there is any I/O problem
 */
public URL url() throws IOException {
    return new URL(this.jsn.text("url"));
}
/**
 * When this comment was created.
 * @return Date of creation
 * @throws IOException If there is any I/O problem
 */
public Date createdAt() throws IOException {
    try {
        return new Github.Time(
            this.jsn.text("created_at")
        ).date();
    } catch (ParseException ex) {
        throw new IOException(ex);
    }
}
```

We should do this for all our `Smart` classes, not just `Comment.Smart`.
